'''Arkady Ivanovich Volsky''' (15 May 1932 &ndash; 9 September 2006) was a Russian politician and businessman. He served as a senior aide to three Soviet presidents, including [[Mikhail Gorbachev]]. He was founder and the first head of [[Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs|the Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs (RSPP)]].

==Early life and education==
Volsky was born in [[Dobrush]], now in [[Belarus]], on 15 May 1932.<ref name=reg10sep>{{cite news|title=Vladimir Putin presents his condolences to family of Arkady Volsky|url=http://regnum.su/english/russia/702425.html|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=Regnum|date=10 September 2006}}</ref><ref name=bar2011>{{cite journal|last=Barnes|first=Andrew|title=Do We Have A Winner?|journal=Ponars  Eurasia|date=November 2011|series=Working Papers|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~ieresgwu/assets/docs/ponars/BarnesWPnov2011.pdf|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> He was raised in an orphanage.<ref name=Kramer>{{cite news|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|title=Arkady I. Volsky, 74, Founder Of Russian Business Lobby|work=The New York Times|page=13|date=13 September 2006|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/13/business/worldbusiness/13volsky.html}}</ref><ref name=tmt11sep/> He studied metallurgy at [[Moscow Institute of Steel and Alloys]]<ref name=Inc1993>{{cite book|title=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=aQsAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35|accessdate=30 March 2013|date=1993-01 - 1993-02|publisher=Educational Foundation for Nuclear Science, Inc.|pages=35|id={{ISSN|00963402}}}}</ref><ref name=aze10sep>{{cite news|title=Died Arkady Volsky, the former chairman of the Special Committee of Nagorno-Karabakh|url=http://www.aze.az/eng.php?id=918|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=AZE|date=10 September 2006}}</ref> and graduated with an engineering degree in 1955.<ref name=tjc2004>{{cite journal|title=Mr. Arkady Volsky: We need resolute actions, not imitation of reforms|journal=The Chemical Journal|date=April 2004|url=http://www.tcj.ru/en/no19/apr04.pdf|accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=kel10sep>{{cite news|last=Keller|first=Bill|title=Around Gorbachev, Centrifugal Forces|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/10/weekinreview/around-gorbachev-centrifugal-forces.html|accessdate=31 March 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=10 September 1989}}</ref>

==Career==
After graduation, Volsky started his career as an assistant foreman at Likhachyov car plant in [[Moscow]].<ref name=reg10sep/><ref name=tjc2004/> In 1969, he became [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|the Communist Party]]'s top representative at the factory.<ref name=inde13sept/> Then he began to work at the machine-building or the engineering industry department of the party.<ref name=reg10sep/><ref name=Inc1993/> During this period he gained influence over the Soviet directorial corps.<ref name=bulletin93/>

He served as a senior aide to three Soviet presidents.<ref name=inde13sept>{{cite news|title=Arkady Volsky: Kremlin troubleshooter|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/arkady-volsky-415732.html|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=The Independent|date=13 September 2006}}</ref> His first post of advisor was in 1983 for then the Soviet president [[Yuri Andropov]] concerning economic affairs.<ref name=jbg19nov>{{cite journal|last=Gayner|first=Jeffrey B.|coauthors=Ariel Cohen; Natalia Kuznetsova|title=Who's Who in The Russian Elections|journal=The Heritage Foundation|date=19 November 1993|url=http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/1993/11/whos-who-in-the-russian-elections|accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref> He continued to served as an assistant on economic affairs to next president [[Konstantin Chernenko]].<ref name=inde13sept/><ref name=staar12nov/> When Chernenko died in 1985, Volsky became a senior aide to next Soviet president [[Mikhail Gorbachev]].<ref name=inde13sept/> On 24 July 1988, Volsky was named as the representative of [[Politburo of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union|the Politburo]] in [[Karabakh Republic|the Karabakh province]] or governor of the province.<ref name=bulletin93/><ref name=Waal2003>{{cite book|author=Thomas De Waal|title=Black garden: Armenia and Azerbaijan through peace and war|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=pletup86PMQC&pg=PA191|accessdate=30 March 2013|year=2003|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-1945-9|pages=191}}</ref> His official title was "representative of the central committe and surpreme Soviet" in Karabakh.<ref name=Waal2003/> During the same period, he became a member of the Communist Party central committee's division in charge of industry.<ref name=tmt11sep/> On 12 January 1989, Gorbachev appointed him head of an eight-member committee of special administration for [[Nagorny Karabakh]].<ref name=Waal2003/><ref>{{cite web|title=Chronology of events|url=http://files.preslib.az/projects/republic/en/azr6_1.pdf|publisher=Administrative Department of the President of the Republic of Azerbaijan|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> The commission was incapable of settling the dispute.<ref name=Cohen1996>{{cite book|author=Ariel Cohen|title=Russian imperialism: development and crisis|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Lvjw9K8zRwIC&pg=PA135|accessdate=12 April 2013|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-95337-9|pages=135}}</ref> After bloody conflict on 20 January 1990, Volsky and his team left the region.<ref name=Waal2003/> In [[Russian legislative election, 1990|the 1990 elections]], Volsky ran for a parliamentary seat, but he lost the election.<ref name=Inc1993/><ref name=bulletin93/> Shortly after his defeat, Volsky was named as the head of the scientific and industrial union that was a pro-Gorbachev body consisting of the directors of state enterprises.<ref name=bulletin93/>

After the communist regime collapsed, Volksy founded [[Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs|the Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs]] (RSPP), the business lobby, in 1991 and headed it until 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arkady Volsky In Memoriam|url=http://eng.rspp.ru/news/view/1836|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=RSPP|date=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=aslund2007>{{cite book|author=Anders <U+00C5>slund|title=Russia's Capitalist Revolution: Why Market Reform Succeeded and Democracy Failed?|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rAYEwq45fioC&pg=PR19|accessdate=30 March 2013|year=2007|publisher=Peterson Institute|isbn=978-0-88132-537-9|pages=19}}</ref> The RSPP, called "Union of Red Directors" at the beginning of the 2000s, is the successor of the previous USSR scientific and industrial union in [[the Russian Federation]].<ref name=bulletin93/><ref name=icc2003>{{cite web|title=The Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs  (Employers) (RUIE)|url=http://www.hik-russland.de/dateien-de/business-unions-and-associations-in-the-russian-federation.pdf|publisher=International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) and Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Russian Federation|accessdate=12 April 2013|date=November 2003}}</ref><ref name=kuz2000>{{cite journal|last=Kuznetsova|first=Vera|title=Union of Red Directors unites the oligarchs|journal=The Russia Journal|year=2000|issue=87|url=http://www.russiajournal.com/node/4158|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> Alexander Shokhin replaced Volsky in the post.<ref name=pravda99>{{cite news|title=Prominent Russian business leader dies, colleague says|url=http://english.pravda.ru/news/russia/09-09-2006/84363-volsky-0/|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Pravda|date=9 September 2006}}</ref>

In July 1991, Volksy and other prominent politicians such as [[Alexander Nikolaevich Yakovlev|Aleksandr Yakovlev]], [[Eduard Shevardnadze]], [[Gavriil Kharitonovich Popov|Gavriil Popov]] and [[Anatoly Sobchak]] issued a declaration in order to create a movement for democratic reforms.<ref name=deland1994>{{cite journal|last=Dellenbrant|first=Jan <U+00C5>ke|coauthors=Oleg Andreev|title=Russian Politics in Transition: Political Parties and Organizations in Russia and the Murmansk Region|journal=Scandinavian Political Studies, Bind 17|year=1994|volume=2|url=http://www.tidsskrift.dk/index.php/scandinavian_political_studies/article/view/13233/25213|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> In August 1991 after Gorbachev resigned from office, Volsky became a member and deputy chairman of the committee or task force headed by prime minister [[Ivan Silayev]] for operative management of the USSR economy.<ref name=ap24aug>{{cite news|title=Gorbachev resigns as communist leader|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1991/Gorbachev-Resigns-as-Communist-Leader-End-of-Ruling-Party-Seen/id-05b2328482b289961f03f9cd048257bb|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Associated Press|date=24 August 1991|location=Moscow}}</ref> Volsky was in charge with industry and military complex until December 1991.<ref name=reg10sep/> He was also one of the major leaders of Civic Union, a bloc of centrist figures, which was founded in December 1992.<ref name=deland1994/><ref name=Jeffries1993>{{cite book|author=Ian Jeffries|title=The Socialist Economies and the Transition to the Market: A Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=mSN_qmb2tCgC&pg=PA556|accessdate=30 March 2013|year=1993|publisher=Routledge, Chapman & Hall, Incorporated|isbn=978-0-415-07580-0|pages=556}}</ref> The bloc was made up the People's Party of Free Russia led by [[Alexander Rutskoi]], the Socialist Party of the Working People, the Union for Revival of Russia, the Social Democratic Centre headed by Oleg Rumyantsev, and the RSPP and Democratic Reform Movement, both led by Volsky.<ref name=staar12nov>{{cite news|last=Staar|first=Richard F.|title=The Next Coup Attempt In Russia|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-11-12/news/9204120505_1_boris-yeltsin-aleksandr-rutskoi-democratic-reform-movement|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=12 November 1992}}</ref><ref name=deland1994/><ref name=sne8dec>{{cite news|last=Sneider|first=Daniel|title=Many Russian Parties Are called|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1993/1208/08061.html/(page)/2|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor|date=8 December 1993}}</ref> It became very powerful movement in summer 1992.<ref name=Weigle2000>{{cite book|author=Marsha A. Weigle|title=Russia's Liberal Project: State-Society Relations in the Transition from Communism|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=oHgOlnNtG7cC&pg=PA240|accessdate=12 April 2013|year=2000|publisher=Penn State Press|isbn=978-0-271-04363-0|pages=242}}</ref> However, its success did not last long and the bloc was dissolved in summer 1993.<ref name=Weigle2000/><ref name=ellman>{{cite journal|last=Ellman|first=Michael|title=Civic Union|journal=Encyclopedia of Russian History|year=2004|volume=2|issue=11|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3404100264.html|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> Volsky also left the bloc.<ref name=Weigle2000/> 

In June 1995, Volsky was appointed by prime minister [[Viktor S. Chernomyrdin]] as deputy head of the peace mission for the conflict in [[Chechen Republic|the Chechen Republic]].<ref name=boud4july>{{cite news|last=Boudreaux|first=Richard|title=Kremlin Envoy Meets With Chechen Leader in Hide-Out|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-07-04/news/mn-20025_1_chechen-leaders|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 July 1995|location=Moscow}}</ref><ref name=dave27june>{{cite news|last=Carpenter|first=Dave|title=Yeltsin reportedly grants news powers to Chechnya negotiators|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1995/Yeltsin-Reportedly-Grants-New-Powers-to-Chechnya-Negotiators/id-bb0d2188d237c6d09f8383231b3faf80|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Associated Press|date=27 June 1995|location=Moscow}}</ref> Volsky met the Chechen President [[Dzhokar Dudayev|Dzhokar M. Dudayev]] at his mountain hide-out near [[Grozny]] in July 1995.<ref name=boud4july/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Rotar|first=Igor|title=Yel'tsin's Plan & Chechnya's Peace|journal=Perspectives|year=1995|volume=6|issue=4|url=http://digilib.bu.edu/journals/ojs/index.php/perspective/article/view/788/767|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> It was the first meeting between senior Russian and Chechen officials since the beginning of [[First Chechen War|the Chechen war]].<ref name=boud4july/>

==Personal life==
Volsky was married and had two children, a son and a daughter.<ref name=val11sep>{{cite news|last=Korchagina|first=Valeria|title=RSPP Founder Arkady Volsky, 74, Dies|url=http://www.pressmon.com/cgi-bin/press_view.cgi?id=904063|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=The Moscow Times|date=11 September 2006}}</ref> He was described as "a man who is always in the shadows."<ref name=bulletin93>{{cite journal|author=Pavel Gutiontov|title=In the Volsky plan?|journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|date=January-February 1993|url=http://books.google.com.tr/books?id=aQsAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=arkady+volsky++the+Russian+Union+of+Industrialists+and+Entrepreneurs&source=bl&ots=QhVbdNvo3L&sig=yXpqM7_a_9QHNHQx46TAIWpU54A&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3zhoUYf3Aqiw4QSo0oGQDw&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=arkady%20volsky%20%20the%20Russian%20Union%20of%20Industrialists%20and%20Entrepreneurs&f=false|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref>

==Death and burial==
Volsky died of complications of leukemia at age 74 in Moscow on 9 September 2006.<ref name=tmt11sep/><ref name=ria9sep>{{cite news|title=RSPP founder Arkady Volsky dies at 74|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20060909/53689203.html|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=Ria Novoski|date=9 September 2006}}</ref><ref name=rfe11sep>{{cite news|title=Prominent Russian businessman dies|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1143713.html|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Radio Free Europa|date=11 September 2006}}</ref> After civil memorial and church service with the attendance of state and political figures of Russia, businessmen, ambassadors, his body was buried at Moscow's [[Novodevichy Cemetery]] on 12 September 2006.<ref name=tmt11sep>{{cite news|title=RSPP Founder Arkady Volsky, 74, Dies|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-17584260_ITM|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=The Moscow Times|date=11 September 2006}}</ref><ref name=daily14sept>{{cite news|title=Daily News NK-Related News Compiled from Reliable Sources|url=http://www.nkrusa.org/news/daily_news.php?id=90|accessdate=12 April 2013|newspaper=Office of the Republic of Nagharno Karabakh|date=14 September 2006}}</ref>

